<br>
For the record I had my first two sons circumcized and consider it one of the biggest parenting mistakes I've made (and not just because of the physical ramifications).  My most recent born son is intact and the process that brought to that point I consider to be a huge step forward for me, even a sort of &quot;born again&quot;* experience.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
<br>
GUIDE TO THE SCRIPTURES<br>
NATURAL MAN<br>
<br>
See also Born Again, Born of God; Carnal; Fall of Adam and Eve<br>
<br>
A person who chooses to be influenced by the passions, desires, appetites, and senses of the flesh rather than by the promptings of the Holy Spirit. Such a person can comprehend physical things but not spiritual things. All people are carnal, or mortal, because of the fall of Adam and Eve. Each person must be born again through the atonement of Jesus Christ to cease being a natural man.<br>
<br>
 The natural man receiveth not the things of the Spirit, 1 Cor. 2: 14. The natural man is an enemy to God and should be put off, Mosiah 3: 19. He that persists in his own carnal nature remaineth in his fallen state, Mosiah 16: 5 (Alma 42: 7-24; D&amp;C 20: 20). What natural man is there that knoweth these things? Alma 26: 19-22. Natural or carnal men are without God in the world, Alma 41: 11. Because of his transgression, man became spiritually dead, D&amp;C 29: 41. Neither can any natural man abide the presence of God, D&amp;C 67: 12. And man began to be carnal, sensual, and devilish, Moses 5: 13 (Moses 6: 49).<br>
<br>
From LDS guide to scriptures<br>
<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
So...though on the surface some people would say that this is a superficial thing (merely aesthetic preference or &quot;medical&quot; or &quot;hygeine&quot; related)...I think it actually drives right at the heart of the purpose of life.<br>
<br>
Anyway, so, anyone else want to discuss this from historical, religious, cultural and physical standpoints?  I would especially love to hear if anyone else who is Christian, but feels the way I do about this, has studied much about when it was used as a token of the covenant (like what it entailed exactly, why it was chosen, importance of token versus the actual spirit of the covenant, etc).  I have a few of my own ideas about this but I would really like to learn more, so I'm hoping someone out there will have a lot to say from that particular perspective.<br>
<br>
Heidi <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> M2</span><br> <span class=usertitle>Unregistered User</span><br>   <font color=#3333ff>(2/28/03 1:45 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=133.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Circumcision</span><hr size=1> I would argue that the only group to whom it does or should have a religious significance is the Jewish Faith.  I absolutely disagree that the decision is something that God feels one way or another about in our day and age.<br>
<br>
I guess that is a pretty direct way of saying that I do not feel that our choice to circ was in any way related to my spirituality, or lack thereof or that it will in anyway impact the religiosity or faith on my sons.<br>
<br>
<br>
