So..I think in this country it just isn't important...most people are Church of England or Catholic here - and as far as I know, it isn't important in that faith....we also don't have the aspect of &quot;dad looks like it, and I don't want little &quot;Billy&quot; to feel different&quot;, which I think is a big factor in USA. <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.growthspurts.com/drivee/images/434360233606.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#9fb7df><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=whanda>Whanda</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 41<br> <font color=#3333ff>(2/28/03 3:18 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=133.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Spiritual implications</span><hr size=1> OK, he's back to sleep now :-)<br>
<br>
I hear what you are saying Shirene.  I remember at one point thinking almost he same thing, that certainly the Prophets would say something about this if it was really something that mattered.  But at the same time, I could not deny what I was learning about the procedure, and as you know, saying that I do not think favorably of it is an undersatement.  This is not the only topic this has happened for me on either, where somethings I was somewhat ambivalent about at one points suddenly seems to have a very clear right or wrong for me as I learn more about it, and I wonder why on earth the Church leaders aren't saying anything more about it.  But not in the way that you implied, I know what you mean there, I've seen that happen too.  I mean more in a way of just trying to sort through things for myself and what I think about it from a moral and ethical standpoint and figuring out exactly how the Church is supposed to function as far as guidance in these areas.<br>
<br>
Anway, just wanted to share a couple of things that were good food for thought about that.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://library.lds.org/nxt/gateway.dll/Magazines/Ensign/1995.htm/ensign%20october%201995.htm/a%20crisis%20a%20council%20and%20inspired%20leadership.htm?f=templates$fn=document-frame.htm$3.0$q=circumcision%20new%20testament$x=Simple#LPHit1">library.lds.org/nxt/gatew...ple#LPHit1</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>There is no doubt that Peter and the other Brethren knew that the law of Moses was fulfilled. (Latter-day revelation also makes it plain that the law of Moses was fulfilled in Christ; see, for example, 3 Ne. 15:4-5—the Savior’s comments to others who had been practicing the law—as well as Moro. 8:8 and D&amp;C 74.) Obedience to the law of Moses was no longer a requirement for salvation since Jesus had completed his atonement. Missionary work among the Gentile nations could go forth directly and without impediment. Yet still there was that conflict between the doctrine of the Church and Jewish culture. The long-standing cultural tradition persisted among many Jewish members for years, even after the doctrinal question was settled.<br>
<br>
In like manner today, there may be questions on which the doctrinal foundation is clear but on which tradition or custom are so strong that the Brethren are impressed not to take a firmer stand, trusting, as did Church leaders in New Testament times, that if the basic revealed principles are known, the Holy Ghost will eventually lead the adherents to forsake their tradition, or academic popularity, or peer pressure in favor of the word of God.<br>
<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://library.lds.org/nxt/gateway.dll/Magazines/Ensign/1995.htm/ensign%20november%201995.htm/acting%20for%20ourselves%20and%20not%20being%20acted%20upon.htm?f=templates$fn=document-frame.htm$3.0$q=well%20meaning%20young%20people%20acted%20upon$x=Simple#LPHit1">library.lds.org/nxt/gatew...ple#LPHit1</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>It is the responsibility of prophets to teach the word of God—not to spell out every jot and tittle of human behavior. Our moral agency requires us to know good from evil and choose the good.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
It is our responsibility.  That is part of the purupose of this life and why we have agency, so we can come to know for ourselves, not just follow an arbitrary list of instructions with no understanding for ourselves of the principles they are based on or development of our own will.<br>
<br>
I agree that there are some things (like what color the paint the walls <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   ) that God does not have an opinion on, but that does not mean that God has given through his Prophets and exhaustive list of behaviours that we should or should not engage in, again, because ability to discern what is moral and what is not and then act accordingly is exactly what he wants us to develop within ourselves.<br>
<br>
Earlier in Elder Fausts talk (the second one I quoted) he said &quot; The Church counsel in this matter has been clear for many years.&quot;  I think there are a lot of things where we don't see the forest for the trees.  People look for a specific &quot;policy&quot; about some sort of practical application when the principles they are based on are being taught right and left.  I think circumcision falls into this category.<br>
<br>
What I have learned about it is that it was not &quot;made up&quot; by God to used as a token.  Genital &quot;marking&quot; (cutting, mutilation....take your pick) was going on in other cultures as well.  (See the LDS Bible Dictionary)  It was something brought in as a token after the people would not remember using other means.  Personally I think it was more that God resorted to using something base enough to reach the people he was working with.  They were in a very carnal state, and so a very carnal token was used.  It wasn't that it was something Godly that God passed down to man, it was something extremely Carnal that God resorted to as a tool when people would not respond to other methods (I'v touched on this in other threads, but I do believe that God works with man in ways which we are ready for, not because He is weak, but because we are and He wants us to develop through agency, which means sometimes &quot;lower laws&quot; were and are given).<br>
<br>
It became popular in the largely non-Jewish United States as a supposed cure for Masterbation which was thought at the time to cause any number of things from blindness to paralysis.  It did not cure masterbation and we now know that masturbation does not cause those things, yet this very powerful carnal tradition continues to perpetuate itself today under the guise of hygeine and medical benefit for the disease du jour (sp?).<br>
<br>
To prove my point, I would ask whether or not it seems reasonable to gather a sample group of youg women and have their labia cut away (in clean conditions and with adequate anesthia even, which not all infant boys are given for circ here right now).  We could then test to see if this would increase hygeine, save them time in the shower, small better, be easier to care for when they are elderly, decrease (evein if ever so minutely) any type of yeast or urinary tract infections and STDs, and let's not forget to see if men simply find it more attractive or if it &quot;tastes better&quot;.<br>
<br>
Seems like an absurd and even offensive proposal, yet that is what has been done with male circumcision.  The only difference is that it was already going on.  But if something isn't a good reason to start it, then is it a good excuse to continue it?<br>
<br>
OK...It's late and I'm rambling, but I basically wanted to brush upon why I think this is something that runs deep enough that it is something that God does care about.  I believe it is painful and harmful and I think, like I said, when we take a closer look at the context it is happening in we can learn a lot about ourselves and where we stand as far as having overcome the &quot;natural man.&quot;<br>
<br>
I'm looking forward to seeing what is added here tomorrow.<br>
