<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>But surely he wouldn't figure that those people who did have sight and tried to explain to him had no idea what they were talking about would he? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> Comperable does not equate to identical.  The question was posed that a blind person “would know” and therefore “miss” sightedness. My counterpoint was that he may not in fact know or miss, especially if it happened earlier on.  If you are equating blindness to the loss of that little flap of skin, I would call that an unjust comparison if taken to the level of identicalness (beyond awareness of the condition) and I can say from personal experience, guys don’t walk up and discuss it, point it out in public or dwell on it.  You can ask every co-worker I have and maybe 2 of them can tell you if I am circed, but we ALL know who the blind guy is on the first floor.  <br>
<br>
My dislike of the comparison to blindness is based on proportionality.  It is frequently a ‘mountain out of a foreskin’ when debated about the impacts and the tragic horror or abomination being done.  I would equate it to a vestigal tail (as some are fond of trying to ridicule) in that it is a surgical process removing tissues and bears little difference later on in life.  I would also compare it socially to piercing a girl’s ears or the prophylactic removal of tonsils or wisdom teeth.  Can you argue that the person is irrevocably changed in all those instances?  Sure.  Can I argue that those changes are fairly insignificant?  Sure.  <br>
<br>
